                  </hi>. I am a bricklayer, and live at No. 13, Feather<lb></lb>stone-street, City-road. I fixed this copper in the prosecutor's house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380129-name-641" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380129-name-641" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380129-name-641" type="surname" value="CASTELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380129-name-641" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY CASTELL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 184.) At a quarter before ten o'clock, on the 24th of January, I met the prisoner at the corner of High-street, Islington, with this copper and lead—I charged him with stealing it—he told me he got it from Ball's-pond, and would give me no other answer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I said I got it from a man of the name of Simms, who asked me to go with it to Shoe-lane, Holborn—I was going by Ball's-pond with my knott—a man called me, and said, "Master, do you want a job?"—I said, "Yes"—he said, "If you take this, I will give you a half crown"—he helped me up and I was going—I met the policeman, who stopped me. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. I took his shoes off, and they corresponded with the marks in the soot at the house—I have been to Ball's-pond, and can<lb></lb>not find a man of the name of Simms there.</p>
